ce:section.ce:para:
Adsorption isotherms studies are essential for understanding the distribution of adsorbate molecules between solid and liquid phases at equilibrium. The energetic properties of an adsorbent surface (homogeneous or heterogeneous), the type of adsorption surface coverage (multilayer or monolayer), and the adsorption capacities of adsorbents were considered [53]. The adsorption isotherm of BCB dye adsorption was studied with various initial concentrations in the range of 50 and 2000 mg L−1 under constant parameters, such as pH solution: 5, adsorbent dosage: 0.04 g, contact time: 30 min, and temperature: 25 °C. It was apparent that the CoFe2O4@HAp-GQDs adsorption capacity greatly increased to reach a plateau trend, indicating its surface could potentially be saturated by dye molecules at sufficient initial BCB concentrations, whereas its capacity reaches to 136 mg g−1 while BCB concentrations are greater than 400 mg L−1 at 25 °C. Experimental data have been examined and modeled using the four well-known isotherm equations, namely the Temkin, Langmuir, Dubinin − Radushkevich, and Freundlich isotherm equations. Based on the experimental data, a nonlinear least squares regression analysis was carried out using Microsoft Excel Solver (version 2020), and the specific isotherm parameters were evaluated (Fig. 6
                        A and Table 4
                        ).
